          <td valign="top">

<span class="txth1">rcom : Evaluate R (www.r-project.org) code via rcom (windows only)</span> 

<br>
<br>

<!-- karma table -->
<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="1" bordercolor="#000066">
<tr>
  <td class="lightbg"><b>&nbsp;script karma&nbsp;</b></td>
  <td>
    Rating <b>0/0</b>,
    Downloaded by 175  </td>
  <td class="lightbg">
  <b>&nbsp;Comments, bugs, improvements&nbsp;</b>
  </td>
  <td>
    <a href="http://vim.wikia.com/wiki/Script:2991">Vim wiki</a>
  </td>  
</tr>
</table>
<p>

<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
<tr><td class="prompt">created by</td></tr>
<tr><td><a href="/account/profile.php?user_id=4037">Tom Link</a></td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="prompt">script type</td></tr>
<tr><td>ftplugin</td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="prompt">description</td></tr>
<tr><td>The rcom ftplugin uses the RCom interface (<a target="_blank" href="http://rcom.univie.ac.at">http://rcom.univie.ac.at</A>)<br>to the R Statistical Package (<a target="_blank" href="http://www.r-project.org">http://www.r-project.org</A>) for sending <br>code to a running instance of R. This way any R snippet can be easily <br>evaluated in that instance of R GUI.<br><br>After installation, interaction with R via rcom is enabled for all<br>buffers with filetype r. For other filetypes, you can use the<br>functions |rcom#EvaluateInBuffer()|.<br><br>Features:<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- Evaluate R code<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- Omnicompletion for R<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- Maps for normal, visual, and insert mode<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- Keyword map (|K|)<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- Operator<br><br>Normal usage~<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;1. Start an instance of R GUI and load the image you want.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;2. Open an R source file in VIM.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;3. Type &lt;c-cr&gt; to evaluate the current line/visual area in R.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;4. Type [count]+ or +{motion} to evaluate some text in R. (You can <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; type ++ to invoke |+|.)<br><br>Full docs: <a target="_blank" href="http://github.com/tomtom/rcom_vim/blob/master/doc/rcom.txt">http://github.com/tomtom/rcom_vim/blob/master/doc/rcom.txt</A></td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="prompt">install details</td></tr>
<tr><td>Requirements:<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- Windows only (because of rcom)<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- A ruby-enabled version of vim<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- R<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;- A suitable version of rcom (<a target="_blank" href="http://rcom.univie.ac.at">http://rcom.univie.ac.at</A>). The rcom <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;library has to be loaded in R, which should be the default <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;behaviour after installing rcom.<br><br>You can check if your installation meets these requirements by <br>evaluating the following line in vim. If it doesn't print an error, <br>you're ready to go:<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;:ruby require 'win32ole'; r = WIN32OLE.new(&quot;StatConnectorSrv.StatConnector&quot;); r.Init(&quot;R&quot;); r.Close<br><br>It is recommended to set |g:rcom#server| and |g:rcom#reuse| = 1 for <br>improved stability.<br><br>In order to install the vba, open the vba file and type: &gt;<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;:so %<br><br>See :help vimball for details. If you have difficulties or use vim 7.0,<br>please make sure, you have the current version of vimball<br>(<a href="/scripts/script.php?script_id=1502">vimscript #1502</a>) installed or update your runtime.<br><br><a target="_blank" href="http://github.com/tomtom/rcom_vim">http://github.com/tomtom/rcom_vim</A></td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
</table>

